Human Activity Recognition

Eric Rodriguez

February 28, 2016

Background

Using devices such as Jawbone Up, Nike FuelBand, and Fitbit it is now possible to collect a large amount of data about personal activity relatively inexpensively. These type of devices are part of the quantified self movement a group of enthusiasts who take measurements about themselves regularly to improve their health, to find patterns in their behavior, or because they are tech geeks. One thing that people regularly do is quantify how much of a particular activity they do, but they rarely quantify how well they do it. In this project, the goal is to use data from accelerometers on the belt, forearm, arm, and dumbell of 6 participants. They were asked to perform barbell lifts correctly and incorrectly in 5 different ways. More information is available from the website here: http://groupware.les.inf.puc-rio.br/har (see the section on the Weight Lifting Exercise Dataset). This project pretends to predict the manner in which they did the exercise using machine learning algorithms.

Obtaining the data

training_url <- "https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-training.csv"
testing_url <- "https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-testing.csv"
training <- read.csv(training_url, header = TRUE, na.strings = c("NA", ""))
testing <- read.csv(testing_url, header = TRUE, na.strings = c("NA", ""))

#remove predictors with more than 30% NAs
training <- training[, colSums(is.na(training)) < round(nrow(training)*0.3)]

Splitting and preprocessing

Given the nigh number of variables, Ill use the Principal Components Analysis method to reduce the number of variables while trying to retain a 95 cumulative percent of variance.

set.seed(2802)
inTrain <- createDataPartition(y=training$classe, p=0.70, list=FALSE)
trainSet <- training[inTrain,]
testSet <- training[-inTrain,]

# Center and scale all variables except 'classe'
preObj <- preProcess(subset(trainSet, select = -c(classe)), method="pca", thresh = 0.95)
# Let's look at the 12 most relevant ones
head(sort(abs(preObj$rotation[,1]), decreasing = TRUE), 12)

Model building

Ill build a Gradient Boosting Machines (GBM)

set.seed(2802)
ctrl <- trainControl(preProcOptions = list(thresh = 0.95))
# Calculate the number of cores
ncores <- detectCores() - 1
# Initiate cluster
cl <- makeCluster(ncores)
registerDoParallel(cl)
modelGBM <- train(classe ~ ., method="gbm", data=trainSet, verbose=FALSE)
stopCluster(cl)

trellis.par.set(caretTheme())
plot(modelGBM)
